John Edward: Linguistic skills are essential to the citizens of the world
Private schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another crop of outstanding results in exams, which is only reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other community subjects.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council for Private Schools (SCIS for their acronyms in English), strive to offer the top level to pupils and ace their parents.
Private schools are aimed at preparing their pupils for higher education, for the career they choose and their place as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and put into practice a custom study plan, we are seeing that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, that gets to his head.
But if you talk to him in his own language, he'd come to the heart."
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot depend solely on English when we want to establish relationships and trust with people from other countries.
Of the results of this year's recent exams, we can see that the languages are at the highest of the board and with the highest approval fees in private schools.
Some 68% of pupils who studied foreign languages were given an outstanding one.
Data, recompiled from the 74 schools that make up CSIS, shows that 72% of pupils obtained Mandarin honours enrollment, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish, also achieved an outstanding one.
This shows that Scottish private schools support languages and consider them key skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are currently having the same consideration as subjects such as science, technology, engineering and mathematics in private school programs and of all kinds.
A survey conducted by the UK's Commission for Employment and Formation in 2014, indicated that among lack of language knowledge it constitutes 17% of the reasons why employers are costing them to fill the vacancies.
Therefore, linguistic skills are increasingly essential in preparing the youth for their future careers.
These skills are essential in a globalized world, as more labor possibilities exist that require idioms.
Regardless of the chosen race, if they learn a second language they will have a real advantage in the future with a life-for-life ability such as this.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will place a bilingual person directly at the head of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey among over 4,000 British adults in 2013, 75% spoke no foreign languages well enough to maintain a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a percentage of two digits, in this case by 15%.
That's why it's so important to invest in a language for kids these days.
Knowing multiple languages, especially those in developing economies, provides children with more opportunities to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, teaching languages differ by school.
Some schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others are decanted by languages considered more important for the UK from 2020 onwards, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Regardless of what their children's interests are, private schools always have several languages to choose from and specialist teachers in this field.
Scottish private schools specialise in providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed, whatever it is whatever sets the future for them.
We cannot deny that at this time, in a global business environment, that languages remain of vital importance to the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered "international communicative skills".
Private schools will continue to offer this diversity and excellence for Scottish youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edwards is a director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
