While Ri resumed the already well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "gradual" denuclearization by virtue of which North Korea would be rewarded as it adopted measures, his statement seemed important, as it did not reject unilateral denuclearization as had occurred with Pyongyang in the past.
Ri made reference to a joint statement made by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a U.S. president in active and a North Korean leader held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim committed to the "denuclearization" of the Korean peninsula as long as Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking from mother-time a formal ending for the 1950-53 Korean War, but United States stated that first Pyongyang must depose its nuclear weapons.
Washington also resisted relaxing harsh international sanctions on North Korea.
"United States insists on 'denuclearization first' and increases pressure by sanctions to achieve its objective of coercive eito, and even opposes the 'declaration of the end of the war'," Ri claimed.
"The perception that penalties can make us kneel down is an impossible dream, for those who do not know us.
