Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader mentioned at the United Nations earlier in the week.
However, he spoke of three meetings between Kim and the leader of South Korea, Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added, "If the other part of this theme of denuclearization was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the corea peninsula would not have reached a dead point."
Still, the tone of Ri's speech was radically different than last year's, when he told the United Nations General Assembly it proved inevitable to attack the United States with North Korean missiles after the "evil president" Trump called Kim "a rocket man on a suicide mission.
This year at the UN, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim for his bravery in taking steps for disarmament, but said that there is still a lot of work left to be done and that sanctions must be maintained until North Korea denuclearizes itself.
