This year, a new Harvard University course is causing all of its students to sleep more with the aim of combating the growing machista culture of studying all night stimulated by caffeine.
An academic found that students in the number one college in the world frequently are unaware of the basic aspects about how to care for them themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Woman's Hospital, conceived the course, which he believes is the first of this type in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the impact the lack of sleep had on learning.
"At the end of the course, a girl came up and told me, 'Why do they just tell me this now, in my senior year?'
He said no one had told him about the importance of sleeping, which surprised me," he commented to The Telegraph.
The course, which was launched this year for the first time, explains to students the basic aspects about how acquiring good sleep habits helps with academic and athletic performance, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard School of Medicine and executive director of the university's health services, stated that the university decided to present the course after finding that students had a significant lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour duration course involves a series of interactive tasks.
In a section there is a picture of a dormitory, where students click coffee bowls, curtains, shapers and books to get information about the effects of caffeine and light and how sleep deficit affects athletic performance, as well as the importance of having a routine at bedtime.
In another section, participants are reported to how lack of prolonged sleep can increase the risk of heart attacks, brain melts, depression, and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know it will not change the students' behavior immediately.
But we believe they have the right to know this information, in the same way we are entitled to know what the health effects are if we chose to smoke tobacco," added Professor Czeisler.
The pride culture of spending the entire night awoke still exists, he claims, and adds that modern technology and the increasing pressure for students who involved sleeplessness was a growing problem.
Ensuring that he sleeps long enough and that he has a good quality sleep must be a student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he points out.[citation needed] Even to avoid becoming fat, as lack of sleep causes the brain to enter into inanition mode, which causes him to constantly be hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, after having attended one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to propel a course across campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to apply for all post-degree students to complete a similar program of study before joining the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended students to consider the option of setting an alarm to lie down, as well as when aroused.[citation needed] As well, it is recommended that they be aware of the harmful effects of "blue light" emitting the electronic displays and LED lighting, which can unbalance circadian rhythm and provoke sleeping problems.
