A further investigation that is being carried out on a stake from the Highlands of Scotland is intended to reveal how bats use the landscape to seek nourishment.
Results are expected to shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation activities.
This study led by scientists from the association National Trust for Scotland will follow the bats Pipistrellus pygmaeus and Pipistrellus pipistrellus, as well as the bat Myotis daubentonii and Plecotus auritus in the Inverewe gardens at Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed in key locations around the property to keep track of bats activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys of manual detectors.
An audio analysis conducted by experts of all recordings will determine the frequency of bat calls and what each species is doing.
A habitat map will then be drawn up to create a detailed image at the scale of the landscape of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS Nature Conservation Advisory, hopes that results will show which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each of the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creation of prairies and what is the best way to keep forests for bats and other associated species.
Populations of bats in Scotland and across the UK have declined considerably in the last century.
These animals are threatened by construction and development works affecting nests and habitat loss.
Aerogenerators and aluminuming also pose a risk, as well as traps with glue for flies, some chemical treatments of building materials, and the attacks of domestic cats.
Bats aren't blind,
but because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes at hunting time.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to locate insects and obstacles in their flight trajectory.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens, and 76,000 acres of land throughout the country, is taken very seriously by bats.
It features ten trained experts, who conduct surveys periodically, nest surveys and, on occasion, even rescues.
The organisation counts even with Scotland's only and first bat reserve at Thrave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of the ten bat species in Scotland.
Estate manager David Thompson states that this is the ideal territory for them.
"In Threave we have a large area for batsmen," he states.
"We count on old buildings, historic trees and a stupendous habitat.
But it's many things we don't know about bats yet, so the work we carry out here and on other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive."
It stresses the importance of controlling the presence of bats before performing maintenance tasks on the properties, as it is possible that the involuntary destruction of a single maternity nest could kill up to 400 females and nurseries, which could exterminate an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass or molest them, as well as destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish official for the organisation Bat Conservation Trust, encourages people to help:
"A lot remains to be learned about bats and, in the case of many of the species, we don't know how it's going to their populations."
