30-year-old Saipov reportedly used a Home Depot rent truck to carry out an attack on a bike lane off Lower Manhattan's West Side Highway Avenue, drying the lives of pedestrians and cyclists he found on his way in October.
To justify the death penalty, prosecutors will have to show that Saipov "intentionally killed" the eight victims and that it resulted in them "intensely" serious injuries, according to the notification of the intent for a death penalty request presented in the Southern District of New York.
Both offences involve the possibility of applying the death penalty according to the court document.
Weeks after the attack occurred, a federal jury filed Saipov with an imputation of 22 felonies, among which were to be included eight murder offences in collaboration with an organized crime group, practice routinely used by prosecutors of organized crime cases, and a crime of violence and destruction of motor vehicles.
The attack required a "notable planning and premeditation", prosecutors declared in describing the way Saipov carried out the "trocious, cruel and depraved" heeded.
"Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov has resulted in injuries, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco" as stated in the notification of intent for prosecution.
Five of the victims were Argentine tourists.
For a decade now the Southern District of New York has not prosecuted a death penalty case.
The accused, Khalid Barnes, was convicted of murdering two drug dealers, but was eventually sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The last time the death penalty was applied in a New York federal case was in 1953, in the case of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a marriage that was executed after being convicted of conspiracy to commit espionage for the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
The Rosenbergs were executed in the electric chair on June 19, 1953.
Uzbekistan-born Saipov demonstrated a lack of regret during the days and months after the attack according to court documents.
He stated to investigators that he felt well for what he had done, as police asserted.
Saipov stated to authorities that in order to carry out the attack, he was inspired by the ISIS videos he visualized on his phone according to the accusation.
He also requested to be able to see the ISIS flag in his hospital room, police claimed.
He pleaded not guilty to the charge of 22 offences.
David Patton, one of the federal trade attorneys charged with representing Saipov, indicated that they were "obviously disappointed" with the prosecution's decision.
"We believe the decision to request the death penalty rather than accept a statement of guilt with life imprisonment without the possibility of repeal will only prolong trauma occasioned by these events for all persons involved," Patton commented.
Saipov's defense team had previously asked prosecutors not to apply for the death penalty.
